subSubSection.paragraph:
Pronotum with numerous club-like setae (
Figs 65, 66 , 68
). The most numerous setae are around and in the middle of tergite, along body axis. Meso-, metanotum and each abdominal tergite with two irregular rows of clublike setae connected together on sides (
Figs 67, 69 , 70
). Numerous club-like setae occur on lateral side of meso- and metanotum and on lateral side of abdominal tergites around each spiracle. Each abdominal tergite with two irregular rows of club-like setae connected together on sides (
Figs 71–74
).

Pro-, meso-, and metasternum with numerous pointed setae distributed in groups: two numerous groups at anterior border medially, two less numerous posteriorly and one numerous at base of each leg. Setae in groups at base of legs as numerous as setae in the groups at anterior border of sternites. Each abdominal sternite with numerous setae distributed regularly on entire surface (
Figs 84–86
). Number of setae on abdominal sternites decreases posteriorly. The longest and the most numerous are pointed setae placed in the middle of sternites I–III (
Figs 83, 84
).

Nine pairs of spiracles: one pair on thorax and 8 on abdomen (
Figs 91–94
). Spiracle of segment VIII very small. Inner wall of spiracles covered with fine asperites, entrance is closed by long filamentous structures (
Figs 91–94
). Edge of each spiracle opening partially with finger-like structures distributed regularly one by another (
Figs 92, 93
).

Six stemmata on each side of head (
Figs 96, 98
).

Head with numerous club-like setae regularly distributed on frons (
Figs 18
,
95, 98–102
), each side of vertex with four minute setae (
Fig. 97
), temporal side with four club-like setae (
Fig. 19
).

